1
00:00:00,599 --> 00:00:05,009
If you’re looking for the most effective
strategies to trade price action, I want your

2
00:00:05,009 --> 00:00:10,560
full attention, because I’m about to reveal
my most important tactics after over 10 years

3
00:00:10,560 --> 00:00:12,120
of price action trading.

4
00:00:12,120 --> 00:00:16,491
We’re not going to talk about support or
resistance, candlestick patterns, or chart

5
00:00:16,491 --> 00:00:17,491
patterns.

6
00:00:17,491 --> 00:00:23,000
I will share something more important: how
to read price action momentum and how to decode

7
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:24,730
the market rhythm.

8
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:29,090
And if you want to show your support, please
leave a like to help us with Youtube algorithm

9
00:00:29,090 --> 00:00:34,220
and turn on the bell, so you don’t miss
when new videos are released.

10
00:00:34,220 --> 00:00:38,829
Traders often have this big obstacle: they
aren’t able to recognize if the market,

11
00:00:38,829 --> 00:00:41,329
today, is trending or ranging.

12
00:00:41,329 --> 00:00:42,769
Here’s your first lesson.

13
00:00:42,769 --> 00:00:48,030
The moment you recognize what type of day
you are dealing with, then you can apply the

14
00:00:48,030 --> 00:00:50,109
appropriate methods for trading.

15
00:00:50,109 --> 00:00:52,940
If it’s trending, pullbacks are the best
choices.

16
00:00:52,940 --> 00:00:58,239
It doesn’t matter whether it’s the first
or second pull- back; a one bar pullback or

17
00:00:58,239 --> 00:00:59,519
complex pullback.

18
00:00:59,519 --> 00:01:05,190
If it’s a trading range day, you only enter
at the extremes of the range, wait for clear

19
00:01:05,190 --> 00:01:10,680
confirmation and stay out of the middle because
it can be very choppy.

20
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:15,799
In order to read the market and to evaluate
the price momentum, I use price action.

21
00:01:15,799 --> 00:01:20,689
The main reason I prefer price action instead
of employing indicators is that indicators

22
00:01:20,689 --> 00:01:23,939
will lose their powers when the market is
not trending.

23
00:01:23,939 --> 00:01:27,289
They create all kinds of false signals on
a Range day.

24
00:01:27,289 --> 00:01:33,380
That is a big problem because market is rotating
in sideway motion over 70% of the time.

25
00:01:33,380 --> 00:01:38,450
One thing I discovered through many years
of trading is that trading ranges is surprising

26
00:01:38,450 --> 00:01:39,719
predictable!

27
00:01:39,719 --> 00:01:44,049
The reason behind this is because the market
is in a zone of “fair value of price”,

28
00:01:44,049 --> 00:01:48,570
where the buyers and sellers are somewhat
“passive”.

29
00:01:48,570 --> 00:01:52,859
Here are several strategies which can help
you to potentially tell what type of day is

30
00:01:52,859 --> 00:01:54,070
ahead.

31
00:01:54,070 --> 00:01:57,749
First we’ll talk about price action during
trending days.

32
00:01:57,749 --> 00:01:59,090
1.

33
00:01:59,090 --> 00:02:03,390
Strength and follow ups
On a trending day, whether it’s an uptrend

34
00:02:03,390 --> 00:02:09,090
or a downtrend, the bar which initiate the
trend usually have decent follow ups.

35
00:02:09,090 --> 00:02:11,030
Market has a rhythm, like music.

36
00:02:11,030 --> 00:02:16,080
You can sense the urgency in tempo and strength
behind every bar when it’s forming.

37
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:20,830
One side is dominating the other one and this
should be fairly obvious.

38
00:02:20,830 --> 00:02:26,591
In a strong uptrend, the chart is filled with
green trend bars with average size body, but

39
00:02:26,591 --> 00:02:28,110
closed high.

40
00:02:28,110 --> 00:02:32,660
Bars are slowly moving upwards which can create
a parabolic curve.

41
00:02:32,660 --> 00:02:37,720
Any pullback red bar is short lived with narrow
body and long wicks at the bottom.

42
00:02:37,720 --> 00:02:42,530
At a glance, there are just simply more green
bars than red bars!

43
00:02:42,530 --> 00:02:46,710
When a strong uptrend is in progress, it’s
very hard to make money selling.

44
00:02:46,710 --> 00:02:50,910
But for buyers, you should see profit not
long after you entered.

45
00:02:50,910 --> 00:02:56,020
The price is pushed up and nobody is taking
profit, until it reaches a fairly strong supply

46
00:02:56,020 --> 00:02:57,020
zone.

47
00:02:57,020 --> 00:03:02,350
Any countertrend attempt will fail and becomes
the most reliable setup to resume the trend.

48
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:08,880
The wick of a candle is very important in
price action trading, it shows both rejection

49
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:09,880
and strength.

50
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:12,820
It’s the hidden truth about domination.

51
00:03:12,820 --> 00:03:17,420
In an uptrend, you should see long wicks at
the bottoms of the bars, not on top.

52
00:03:17,420 --> 00:03:22,160
It means any selling is being rejected and
pushed up.

53
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:24,910
The same principles apply for downtrend.

54
00:03:24,910 --> 00:03:30,180
More consecutive red bars with average size
body and wicks on top of the bars.

55
00:03:30,180 --> 00:03:33,840
Any green bar pullback is small and short-
lived.

56
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:36,090
Here we had a very strong downtrend.

57
00:03:36,090 --> 00:03:39,350
There are few green bars, and many bearish
bars.

58
00:03:39,350 --> 00:03:42,220
The close of each candle is lower than previous
close.

59
00:03:42,220 --> 00:03:46,590
It’s in parabolic curve rather than boxed-in.

60
00:03:46,590 --> 00:03:52,020
Ina trending day, a market controlled by bulls
is often characterized by the following bar

61
00:03:52,020 --> 00:03:55,850
patterns:
First, then obvious one is that we have more

62
00:03:55,850 --> 00:03:58,490
bull bars than bears bars.

63
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:03,200
When he see this on our charts, this means
that the bulls have more power and are increasingly

64
00:04:03,200 --> 00:04:09,340
moving the market upwards
Also, we will see consecutive bull bars.

65
00:04:09,340 --> 00:04:13,220
Consecutive bull bars is a clear indication
of a bullish momentum

66
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:17,970
In a bull market, the green bodies are bigger
than the red bodies.

67
00:04:17,970 --> 00:04:22,500
When he see this on our charts that’s a
signal that the bulls have more strength than

68
00:04:22,500 --> 00:04:23,950
the bears.

69
00:04:23,950 --> 00:04:29,240
Also, during a bull controlled market, we
will see the green bars closing near their

70
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:30,390
highs.

71
00:04:30,390 --> 00:04:34,930
This suggests a good momentum on the upside,
because the bulls are trying to maintain the

72
00:04:34,930 --> 00:04:36,320
prices higher.

73
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:40,450
We will also see a lot of wicks below the
green bars.

74
00:04:40,450 --> 00:04:45,210
This also represents a good signal that the
bulls are in control of the market and that

75
00:04:45,210 --> 00:04:48,140
are trying to push the prices upwards.

76
00:04:48,140 --> 00:04:52,990
When we see the green bodies getting bigger
this signals a clear bullish momentum.

77
00:04:52,990 --> 00:04:54,340
2.

78
00:04:54,340 --> 00:05:00,560
The old-school Higher High & Lower Low
First, the follow-up bars should be breaking

79
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:02,590
out previous bars.

80
00:05:02,590 --> 00:05:08,100
For example, each follow up green bar in an
uptrend should have higher low, higher high

81
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:10,530
and higher close to the previous one.

82
00:05:10,530 --> 00:05:16,710
Vice versa for downtrend, red bearish bars
should be making lower low, lower high and

83
00:05:16,710 --> 00:05:20,160
lower close than the previous bar.

84
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:25,930
Another interpretation is based on structural
pattern: The pivot point of each swing.

85
00:05:25,930 --> 00:05:29,110
Price never moves in straight line, it moves
in waves.

86
00:05:29,110 --> 00:05:32,639
And each wave will create pivot point on the
chart.

87
00:05:32,639 --> 00:05:36,990
These pivot points can often be found in pullbacks
of a trend.

88
00:05:36,990 --> 00:05:42,980
They are important turning points which represent
zones of the demand/supply.

89
00:05:42,980 --> 00:05:48,310
The best way to use these pivot points to
identify the trend is to create a trend line

90
00:05:48,310 --> 00:05:51,100
by connecting them with straight lines.

91
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:54,920
You don’t need advanced knowledge to draw
complex trendlines.

92
00:05:54,920 --> 00:06:00,350
Just connect a low and higher low, you get
a simple trendline pointing in an up direction.

93
00:06:00,350 --> 00:06:04,550
For downtrend, connect any high and a lower
high.

94
00:06:04,550 --> 00:06:09,480
This trendline gives you both the direction
of the trend and great reference points for

95
00:06:09,480 --> 00:06:13,190
support/resistance for future price movement.

96
00:06:13,190 --> 00:06:14,590
3.

97
00:06:14,590 --> 00:06:18,950
The dynamic support/resistance tool, namely
EMA (Exponential Moving Average).

98
00:06:18,950 --> 00:06:25,860
I personally use the 20-period EMA on my chart
when trading price action because it’s reacts

99
00:06:25,860 --> 00:06:29,010
to price quickly and follow the price action
closely.

100
00:06:29,010 --> 00:06:34,639
There are many ways of using the EMA, but
I found two methods are quite effective.

101
00:06:34,639 --> 00:06:41,220
First, I use the 20-day EMA to give me a broad
idea of what to expect for the day, whether

102
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:43,620
it’s trending or ranging.

103
00:06:43,620 --> 00:06:50,460
For trending days, bars usually stay consistently
above or below one side of EMA, most of the

104
00:06:50,460 --> 00:06:55,330
time not touching the EMA for hours until
a deeper correction.

105
00:06:55,330 --> 00:07:01,550
For range day, it’s very obvious that price
interacts with EMA very closely.

106
00:07:01,550 --> 00:07:07,400
Another usage for EMA is to watch the price
action around the EMA when it’s touched,

107
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:10,430
and based on the reaction, you find tradable
setups.

108
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:14,080
EMA isn’t like trendline, a straight line.

109
00:07:14,080 --> 00:07:19,330
EMA follows the price and it serves as strong
support/resistance reference point.

110
00:07:19,330 --> 00:07:23,830
But it only works best when price is trending
in one direction.

111
00:07:23,830 --> 00:07:31,070
When price move sideways, EMA lose its efficiency
and does not produce any reliable setups.

112
00:07:31,070 --> 00:07:35,930
As long as price stays above the EMA, you
will only buy, never sell.

113
00:07:35,930 --> 00:07:37,699
The opposite is true for downtrend.

114
00:07:37,699 --> 00:07:43,390
One of the trade model I employ often is to
enter the “1st Deep Pullback”.

115
00:07:43,390 --> 00:07:49,430
In a strong trend, price goes too far away
from the EMA and not touching for hours, but

116
00:07:49,430 --> 00:07:54,800
when it does for the 1st time, this deep pullback
is a very reliable setup to resume the original

117
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:56,400
trend.

118
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:58,960
Some experts call the EMA “the Mean”.

119
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:04,400
When price moves too far away from the “Mean”,
it can create a rubber-band effect, and price

120
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:07,330
would stretch back to the EMA.

121
00:08:07,330 --> 00:08:12,979
Traders watching for the EMA, know that probability
of the 1st pullback of a strong trend to turn

122
00:08:12,979 --> 00:08:15,360
into a reversal is quite rare.

123
00:08:15,360 --> 00:08:21,530
So when price returns to the EMA, they would
enter, hoping the original trend will resume.

124
00:08:21,530 --> 00:08:27,560
Now let’s talk about the Trading Range (Sideway
price action).

125
00:08:27,560 --> 00:08:31,970
Trading ranges can be very tricky because
it’s very difficult to distinguish between

126
00:08:31,970 --> 00:08:33,479
range and trend.

127
00:08:33,479 --> 00:08:37,159
It’s understandable because they have some
similarities.

128
00:08:37,159 --> 00:08:41,669
The relationship between Trend and Range is
that they are interactive.

129
00:08:41,669 --> 00:08:44,209
One can’t survive without the other.

130
00:08:44,209 --> 00:08:46,720
Trend is essentially a breakout phase.

131
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:49,170
Range is essentially a consolidation phase.

132
00:08:49,170 --> 00:08:52,569
And market is rotating between Trend and Range.

133
00:08:52,569 --> 00:08:56,990
So how do you actually read a price action
range.

134
00:08:56,990 --> 00:08:57,990
1.

135
00:08:57,990 --> 00:09:01,660
Wicks
Trading range is filled with wicks especially

136
00:09:01,660 --> 00:09:05,809
more on top and bottom of the approximate
range parameter.

137
00:09:05,809 --> 00:09:09,129
The reason behind this is back to back failure.

138
00:09:09,129 --> 00:09:13,709
When price is being pushed up to the upper
boundary of the range, sellers are letting

139
00:09:13,709 --> 00:09:17,019
it go, to see how far price can go.

140
00:09:17,019 --> 00:09:20,780
The higher it goes, the more profit for sellers
when they sell into it.

141
00:09:20,780 --> 00:09:23,920
It creates a vacuum effect.

142
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:29,410
When price becomes excessive, sellers will
jump in and sell into buyers, pushing the

143
00:09:29,410 --> 00:09:33,069
price towards the lower boundary of the range.

144
00:09:33,069 --> 00:09:37,709
Entering at the extremes offers great risk-reward
ratio for traders.

145
00:09:37,709 --> 00:09:42,670
You should try to embrace range days, because
they are somewhat “predictable”.

146
00:09:42,670 --> 00:09:47,889
And the first step, look for many long wicks
around the edge of the ranges.

147
00:09:47,889 --> 00:09:50,009
Wicks are failures.

148
00:09:50,009 --> 00:09:56,440
Top wick means buyers failed and bottom wicks
means sellers failed.

149
00:09:56,440 --> 00:10:02,819
Remember this: Range will have multiple failed
Breakout attempts before a real breakout.

150
00:10:02,819 --> 00:10:07,490
When the real breakout occurs, you can’t
miss it because it’s convincing both in

151
00:10:07,490 --> 00:10:09,779
volume and bar size!

152
00:10:09,779 --> 00:10:16,029
Any inferior breakout will fail within a short
time, generally within 5 bars.

153
00:10:16,029 --> 00:10:17,910
Look at the wicks within this range.

154
00:10:17,910 --> 00:10:23,730
Observe this area filled with Dojis and bars
that are overlapping.

155
00:10:23,730 --> 00:10:26,630
This bar shows the real breakout of that range.

156
00:10:26,630 --> 00:10:32,569
The bar is forceful, large in size, closed
high and with a minimal wick.

157
00:10:32,569 --> 00:10:33,839
2.

158
00:10:33,839 --> 00:10:37,850
Alternation between bullish and bearish strength

159
00:10:37,850 --> 00:10:39,980
This shows both sides are active.

160
00:10:39,980 --> 00:10:43,220
There is no feeling of continuation of either
side.

161
00:10:43,220 --> 00:10:45,869
There is no consistency in strength from either
side.

162
00:10:45,869 --> 00:10:49,560
The red bars and green bars are somewhat equal
in quantity.

163
00:10:49,560 --> 00:10:53,850
The strength is weak, it shines and dies very
quickly.

164
00:10:53,850 --> 00:10:58,860
Often you will see a gigantic bar in a range,
it take over the whole space.

165
00:10:58,860 --> 00:11:01,759
Then the follow up is on the opposite side.

166
00:11:01,759 --> 00:11:07,850
So no momentum continuation, and traders trying
to trade the first bar are now trapped.

167
00:11:07,850 --> 00:11:09,589
Price moved in the opposite direction.

168
00:11:09,589 --> 00:11:13,559
Again: there is no sense of consistency.

169
00:11:13,559 --> 00:11:19,649
Range days can create a weird feeling that
market is not really active and it feels lazy.

170
00:11:19,649 --> 00:11:25,309
But actually both sides are very active, it
creates an balance between buyers and sellers.

171
00:11:25,309 --> 00:11:29,639
That’s why the price is not breaking out
to any one direction.

172
00:11:29,639 --> 00:11:35,420
All the setups which worked best in trend
trading are now losing their magical power.

173
00:11:35,420 --> 00:11:39,339
Remember this when trading range: Patience!

174
00:11:39,339 --> 00:11:45,649
Wait for confirmation and proof one side is
actually failing, then enter at the extremes!!!

175
00:11:45,649 --> 00:11:46,999
3.

176
00:11:46,999 --> 00:11:50,910
Dojis and Overlapping price action.

177
00:11:50,910 --> 00:11:54,891
When you start to see lots of Dojis and bars
are overlapping (sideways action), market

178
00:11:54,891 --> 00:11:56,709
is probably ranging.

179
00:11:56,709 --> 00:11:59,069
The Dojis are the early signs for Range formation.

180
00:11:59,069 --> 00:12:05,899
A Doji is a one-bar trading range in essence
and it has many variations, “Gravestone”;

181
00:12:05,899 --> 00:12:09,600
“Dragonfly”; “Hammer”; “Hanging
man”.

182
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:16,640
The names are not important, they all indicating
the same character: indecisiveness.

183
00:12:16,640 --> 00:12:21,459
Overlapping price action simply means the
size of the bars are either similar or inside

184
00:12:21,459 --> 00:12:23,160
of each other.

185
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:26,059
Price is moving sideways, is not going anywhere.

186
00:12:26,059 --> 00:12:30,879
Sometimes, you will see two or more bars have
the same High or Low.

187
00:12:30,879 --> 00:12:35,869
Then you look to your left, and you will find
past corresponding price action that stopped

188
00:12:35,869 --> 00:12:37,779
at that level also.

189
00:12:37,779 --> 00:12:42,429
This means there is a strong supply/demand
zone for that level.

190
00:12:42,429 --> 00:12:48,499
So whenever you see two or more bars have
the same High/Low, mark that level, and watch

191
00:12:48,499 --> 00:12:52,509
for reaction when price revisit that level.

192
00:12:52,509 --> 00:12:57,760
Look for reliable setups of real breakout
or failed breakout.

193
00:12:57,760 --> 00:12:59,369
4.

194
00:12:59,369 --> 00:13:01,459
The 20 EMA

195
00:13:01,459 --> 00:13:06,850
When price is trending strong and fast, it’s
hard for EMA to catch up with the price.

196
00:13:06,850 --> 00:13:12,829
Therefore, in a strong trend, there is distance
between EMA and bars.

197
00:13:12,829 --> 00:13:18,000
In trading range, it’s the opposite, there
is lots of touching.

198
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:23,110
Because price movement in a Range is not very
volatile, most of the time it’s not going

199
00:13:23,110 --> 00:13:24,110
anywhere.

200
00:13:24,110 --> 00:13:28,339
The EMA cuts through the range, often in the
middle.

201
00:13:28,339 --> 00:13:33,459
The 20-day EMA is like an axis where price
is moving around it.

202
00:13:33,459 --> 00:13:39,360
There is one scenario to note here: when a
Range is about to break, watch the price action

203
00:13:39,360 --> 00:13:44,980
closely, and you will notice the EMA is somehow
holding the bars and push them out to the

204
00:13:44,980 --> 00:13:46,799
breakout direction.

205
00:13:46,799 --> 00:13:52,889
For an upside breakout, price will stop around
the middle of Range around the EMA.

206
00:13:52,889 --> 00:13:55,189
Vice versa for downtrend.

207
00:13:55,189 --> 00:14:00,199
Price will test EMA and will be pushed to
the downside.

208
00:14:00,199 --> 00:14:04,499
Being able to read a price action chart is
important to make the right decisions.

209
00:14:04,499 --> 00:14:10,149
The problem many traders have is that they
overcomplicate things and get easily confused

210
00:14:10,149 --> 00:14:13,940
– or they don’t have a process in the
first place and don’t know what they are

211
00:14:13,940 --> 00:14:15,100
looking for.

212
00:14:15,100 --> 00:14:21,309
Now, your job is to open your trading platform,
choose one market, and start analyzing price

213
00:14:21,309 --> 00:14:24,379
action using these techniques, just these.

214
00:14:24,379 --> 00:14:30,420
I could have mentioned chart patterns like
flags or triangles, but these are just ranges.

215
00:14:30,420 --> 00:14:36,449
I could have mentioned tens of candlestick
patterns, like inside bars or piercing lines,

216
00:14:36,449 --> 00:14:39,630
but again, these aren’t as important right
now.

217
00:14:39,630 --> 00:14:45,019
What’s important is to decode the market
rhythm, to distinguish a trend day from a

218
00:14:45,019 --> 00:14:48,230
range day and to read price momentum.

219
00:14:48,230 --> 00:14:51,499
This is the best price action approach.

220
00:14:51,499 --> 00:14:56,429
As always, if you got any value from this
and learned something new, leave us a like

221
00:14:56,429 --> 00:15:01,660
to help us with Youtube algorithm, and also,
make sure to enable notifications to stay

222
00:15:01,660 --> 00:15:04,670
in touch when new videos are released.

223
00:15:04,670 --> 00:15:05,100
Until next time.

